{"id":"1411.3262","submitter":"Anush Tserunyan","authors":"Anush Tserunyan","title":"A Ramsey theorem on semigroups and a general van der Corput lemma","comments":"Changes in definitions that make the statements a bit more general\n  and the flow of proofs smoother","journal-ref":"Journal of Symbolic Logic, vol. 81 (2016), no. 2, pp. 718--741","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO math.CO math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A major theme in arithmetic combinatorics is proving multiple recurrence\nresults on semigroups (such as Szemer\\'edi's theorem) and this can often be\ndone using methods of ergodic Ramsey theory. What usually lies at the heart of\nsuch proofs is that, for actions of semigroups, a certain kind of one\nrecurrence (mixing along a filter) amplifies itself to multiple recurrence.\nThis amplification is proved using a so-called van der Corput difference lemma\nfor a suitable filter on the semigroup. Particular instances of this lemma (for\nconcrete filters) have been proven before (by Furstenberg,\nBergelson--McCutcheon, and others), with a somewhat different proof in each\ncase. We define a notion of differentiation for subsets of semigroups and\nisolate the class of filters that respect this notion. The filters in this\nclass (call them $\\partial$-filters) include all those for which the van der\nCorput lemma was known, and our main result is a van der Corput lemma for\n$\\partial$-filters, which thus generalizes all its previous instances. This is\ndone via proving a Ramsey theorem for graphs on the semigroup with edges\nbetween the semigroup elements labeled by their ratios.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Nov 2014 17:59:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Apr 2017 18:10:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-04-18"}
